Q 7: Erythema nodosum

[!TIP] Painful Panniculitis with Plethora of causes.

[!TIP] Mnemonic:
NODOSUM
N : No causes in 80% of cases
O : Obstetric -> Pregnancy
D : Drugs (sulfonamides; amoxicillin)
O : Oral contraceptive pills
S : Sarcoidosis/ Tuberculosis
U : Ulcerative colitis; Crohn's disease; Behcet disease
M: Micro

  • Viral : HSV; EBV; Hep B; Hep C
  • Bacterial: campylobacter; salmonella; streptococci; Brucellosis
  • Parasite : Amoebiasis; Giardiasis

[!INFO] Stimuli for parathyroid hormone secretion
Important triggers for PTH secretion are

  1. hypocalcemia and
  2. hyperphosphatemia Source
    [!INFO] Net effect: Ca and Phosphate
    Main action is to 'mobilize calcium from bone' and increase renal phosphate excretion.
  • osteoclastic activity in bone (a rapid response)
  • intestinal absorption of calcium VIA production of calcitriol (which takes about 1 day to respond)
  • 1-hydroxylation of vitamin D (the rate-limiting step)
  • renal tubular reabsorption of calcium.
  • It has a phosphaturic action (by inhibiting NaPi-IIa active transporter which is found in the PCT)
    • Mnemonic: PTH PCT
  • Parathyroid hormone secretion is directly inhibited by high calcium levels.
  • This happens through binding of calcium to a GPCR on the parathyroid cells called CaR.

    Source
  • Physiological compensatory mechanism for hypocalcemia.
  • Therefore, PTH levels, but normal calcium level.
  • Occurs in CKD.
  • Chronically elevated PTH levels can cause osteitis fibrosa cystica. (high turnover bone disease)
  • After chronic secondary hyperparathyroidism, gland becomes autonomous.
  • Usually occurs in CKD.
  • There is refractory hypercalcemia and and Phosphate
  • Refractory to medical treatment
  • Some experts diagnose this condition once renal transplant has also failed to normalize calcium levels.
  • Surgical excission of the parathyroids is done for treatment.
  • pathology: Parathyroid nodules acquire autonomous function and autonomously secrete parathyroid hormone.
    In hypoparathyroidism, there is increased bone mineral density. But the bone is not properly formed.
    The signs of acute hypoparathyroidism are due to hypocalcemia.
  • Signs are neuronal excitability: carpopedal spasm and tetany.
    • Perioral numbness, paraesthesia of hands and feet
    • Chvosteks and Tousseau's sign (the latter is more sensitive and specific)
  • Prolonged QT interval.
  • Management
    • IV Calcium gluconate
    • Oral calcitriol

[!INFO] Serum PTH can be interpreted correctly only when serum calcium is measured simultaneously

  • Hypocalcemia with low or inapproprirately normal PTH level
  • Commonest cause is post surgical. (roughly 80%)
  • If not that, it is autoimmune. (roughly 20%)
  • Caused by a defect in PTH receptor caused by mutation of a protein coupled to the receptor (GNAS-1)
  • Results in end organ resistance to PTH
  • Biochemical manifestations are just like hypoparathyroidism (Low Ca2+ and high Phosphate)
  • BUT having HIGH PTH level
    • associated with low IQ, short stature, shortened 4th and 5th metacarpals

Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy (AHO) is a characteristic skeletal phenotype, including short stature, obesity, round face, and brachydactyly. AHO appears in patients with pseudohypoparathyroidism (PHP) who have resistance to PTH and in their eumetabolic family members who have pseudopseudohypoparathyroidism (PPHP).

Bind to bone hydroxyapetite and inhibit osteoclasts.

  • Alendronate and risendronate - once weekly dose
  • ibandronate - once monthly.
  • Zoledronate - once yearly infusion
  • beware! osteonecrosis of the jaw! -> occurs with HIGH dose IV bisphophonates.

  • Notes: release of niacin from certain legumes like corn is possible only when the corn is prepared in alkaline medium (tortias). So pellagra can be prevalent even in areas which have abundance of legumes. (i.e India)

  • Infantile beri beri occurs when mom is B1 deficient and breast milk has low B1 => Cardiomegaly, tachycardia, dyspnoea, vomiting etc.

  • Adult beri beri into wet and dry

  • Triad of OPHTHALMOPLEGIA, ataxia, confusion, + nystagmus + lower limb polyneuropathy.

Dry beriberi:
is the development of a symmetrical peripheral neuropathy characterized by both sensory and motor impairments, mostly of the distal extremities.(peripheral neuropathy, muscle weakness, brisk tendon reflexes, seizures).
"Dry beriberi is characterized by severe burning dysesthesias (feet more than hands), weakness and wasting (distal more than proximal), trophic changes (shiny skin, hair loss), and acrodistal sensory loss in a graded fashion typical of dying-back polyneuropathies."
Wet beriberi
includes signs of cardiac involvement with cardiomegaly, cardiomyopathy, High output heart failure, peripheral edema, and tachycardia, in addition to neuropathy

Pyoderma gangrenosum

Pyoderma gangrenosum (PG) is a rare neutrophilic dermatosis that presents with rapidly developing, painful skin ulcers hallmarked by undermined borders and peripheral erythema. Epidemiological studies indicate that the average age of PG onset is in the mid-40s. Source

  • Acute onset
  • Purpule
  • Undermined edge
  • Painful
  • Multiple ulcers

Biopsy: neutrophilic infiltrate.
